CROSS‑REFERENCE VERIFICATION ENGINE (CRVE)

Unified Specification — Rev Ω.1

The CRVE is the subsystem that replaces the old “Domain” concept entirely.
It is not a domain module — it is a truth‑checking engine that sits between AERION and the Ω‑Core.

Its job is simple:

Take the abstracted representation from AERION, verify it against external reality, and quantify trust.

It does this using:

• search engine queries
• AI model queries
• cross‑reference comparison
• a traffic‑light trust system
• a numerical trust code


This gives Omricon a real‑world grounding layer without contaminating the core architecture.

---

⭐ 1. Purpose of the CRVE

The CRVE exists to:

• verify claims
• detect contradictions
• detect missing information
• quantify trust
• provide external grounding
• prevent hallucination
• feed trust metrics into the Ω‑Core

This is the external truth interface of Omricon.

(See: Traffic‑Light Trust System)

---

⭐ 2. Position in the Pipeline

VORIN
→ SERA
→ AERION
→ CRVE
→ Ω‑Core
→ Governor
→ Output

The CRVE is the only layer allowed to interact with external data sources.

---

⭐ 3. CRVE Components

The CRVE consists of four deterministic subsystems:

3.1 Search Engine Query Unit

Queries external search engines for factual grounding.

3.2 AI Reasoning Query Unit

Queries an AI model for pattern‑based reasoning.

3.3 Cross‑Reference Comparator

Compares search results and AI reasoning for:

• overlap
• contradictions
• missing data
• consistency
• confidence

3.4 Trust Scoring Engine

Outputs:

• traffic‑light trust rating
• numerical trust code
• trust lineage

This is fed directly into the Ω‑Core.

---

⭐ 4. CRVE Data Flow

1. AERION produces an abstract representation.
2. CRVE extracts key claims.
3. Search Engine Query Unit retrieves external data.
4. AI Query Unit retrieves model‑based reasoning.
5. Cross‑Reference Comparator evaluates consistency.
6. Trust Scoring Engine produces trust metrics.
7. Ω‑Core uses trust metrics to validate reasoning.
8. Governor enforces behavioural safety.


This is a closed, deterministic loop.

---

⭐ 5. Traffic‑Light Trust System

(See: Traffic‑Light Trust System)

• Green — high agreement
• Amber — partial agreement
• Red — contradiction or missing data

This is the behavioural trust signal.

---

⭐ 6. Numerical Trust Code

(See: Numerical Trust Code)

A score from 0.00 to 1.00 representing:

• consistency
• overlap
• contradiction level
• data completeness
• model confidence

This is the quantitative trust signal.

---

⭐ 7. CRVE → Ω‑Core Interface

The CRVE sends the following to the Ω‑Core:

• trust_score
• trust_light
• cross_reference_report
• contradiction_flags
• missing_data_flags
• external_lineage

The Ω‑Core uses this to:

• validate reasoning
• apply corrections
• halt if unsafe
• request re‑evaluation

(See: Integrate CRVE with Core)

